[[File:Vytenis Jankauskas playing the Lithuanian bagpipes.png|right|thumb|250px|A Lithuanian bagpiper.]]
The '''dūdmaišis''' or '''Labonoro dūda''' is a [[Lithuania]]n [[Bagpipes|bagpipe]]<ref name="Cluj-Napoca2006">{{cite book|author=Biblioteca Centrală Universitară "Lucian Blaga" Cluj-Napoca|title=Philobiblon: bulletin of the "Lucian Blaga" Central University Library|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ebjAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 April 2011|year=2006|publisher=University Press|pages=308 }}</ref> with a single [[chanter]] and [[Drone (music)|drone]]. The Lithuanian bagpipe was traditionally played at a variety of events, including May Day festivities,<ref name="WalfordCox1882">{{cite book|author1=[[Edward Walford]]|author2=[[John Charles Cox]]|author3=George Latimer Apperson|title=The Antiquary: A Magazine Devoted to the Study of the Past|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2JYF1Uj2o2QC&pg=PA185|accessdate=21 December 2012|year=1882|publisher=E. Stock|pages=185–}}</ref> and spring caroling.<ref name="Dahlig2009">{{cite book|author=Piotr Dahlig|title=Traditional Musical Cultures in Central-Eastern Europe. Ecclesiastical and folk transmission|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s6IEh7b6B-QC&pg=PA116|accessdate=21 December 2012|year=2009|publisher=Dahlig|isbn=978-83-89101-86-0|pages=116–}}</ref> A 1955 publication by the [[Lituanus Foundation]] noted that: "The Labanoro Dūda or Bagpipe was at one time very widely used, though it is almost forgotten."<ref name="Foundation1955">{{cite book|author=Lituanus Foundation|title=Lituanus|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iiAJAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=21 December 2012|year=1955|publisher=Lituanus Foundation.}}</ref>

==Players==
*'''Lygaudė''', traditional folk group
*'''Ugniavijas''', traditional men's folk band
*[[Atalyja]], Lithuanian folk-rock band<ref name="Bousfield2011">{{cite book|author=Jonathan Bousfield|title=The Rough Guide to Estonia, Latvia & Lithuania|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hp_bqnvRzMEC&pg=PA384|accessdate=21 December 2012|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-4053-8280-9|pages=384–}}</ref>

